<subSubSection id="9DD3743D0E1768995643BE06E4437304" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph id="42CCDA8F24928B52D01C344E681BE761" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA0DB651ECAC605A04AE0189DFC38C90" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
(partially from Dendy, 1905). Encrusting extensively over calcareous algae and filling crevices, 4.5
<normalizedToken id="6CB1D4601711B6EA0EFF9F5CCA7798F0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.3 cm in lateral expansion. Surface smooth, no apertures. Colour pale grey (alcohol). Consistency tough, fleshy. Dendy mentions the presence of large cells with inclusions (cystencytes) of 60 
<normalizedToken id="99AC4BEF767751B6203EFE3F1996AF89" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4EEF77942965A6720357CE8517FF71AE" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">The two slides contain thin cross sections of the peripheral regions.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE741655A57D98D74DE4B6060D342F33" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Skeleton (Fig. 11A): irregular mass of short-shafted triaenes covered by a thin ectosomal crust of microscleres.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E2FEBAE11621B7C48CFC7DA9E4D31BF" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Spicules: megascleres predominantly dichocalthrops, but also normal calthrops or calthrops with one or two bifid cladi, sanidasters.</paragraph>
